## **Introduction: The Dumbest Decision That Actually Worked**

Picture this: You've got a stable job at Disney. You work on **Star Wars** games. Life is good.

Then you wake up one day and think, "I'm gonna throw all this away and make a game about embalming dead bodies in my bedroom."

That's exactly what **Brian Clarke** did in 2018. And honestly? Best terrible decision ever.

![](https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1766841711555/3fa95e45-bd2a-4564-9df9-d4b2b3634b1f.png align="center")

---

After **13 years** at big studios like EA and Disney, Clarke had achieved everything a game artist could dream of.

But he wanted to make horror games—the weird, creepy kind that big studios avoid. So he quit, started his tiny studio **DarkStone Digital** (fancy name for "just me"), and got to work.

## **The Week That Changed Everything**

Here's where it gets wild.

Clarke was making a different game called "**Our Secret Below**" but needed a creative break. So he gave himself ONE WEEK to make a tiny **horror** prototype.

His thought process was simple: What's creepy? A dead body. Why would you be alone with one? A job. Boom—**embalming game**.

He slapped together a basic prototype with some tools, a few scares, and a corpse that suddenly sits up. Nothing fancy.

Then he released it online to promote his ACTUAL game.

Plot twist: The side project went **viral**.

![](https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1766841738108/ba238387-75b8-4d52-bf5b-2640c89cfc7d.jpeg align="center")

---

YouTubers played it. Thousands watched. Comments exploded with: "WE WANT THE FULL EMBALMING EXPERIENCE."

Clarke looked at his original game, then at this corpse prototype everyone loved, and made the call. He scrapped his plans and went all-in on The Mortuary Assistant.

## **How to Make a Checklist Terrifying**

Here's the genius: the game turns your job into a trap.

Most horror games let you run from monsters. This game? You HAVE to **work**.

You're Rebecca, a mortuary assistant locked in for the night shift. You need to embalm three bodies before sunrise.

Oh, and one's possessed by a demon that wants your **soul**. Better figure out which one.

![](https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1766841766835/36d5957e-3bf6-4cb7-92b6-301d28b4a5aa.avif align="center")

---

The embalming process is detailed: wheel bodies from storage, wire jaws shut, drain fluids, inject chemicals. It's a twisted **job simulator**.

But here's the trick—while you're focused on mixing chemicals, you can't watch your **surroundings**.

The game FORCES you to concentrate on tasks, making you vulnerable to whatever's lurking in your peripheral vision.

Did that shadow move? Was that locker open? Is that hand in a different position?

Clarke built over 100 different scares that trigger based on where you are and what you're doing. The game watches **YOU**, then strikes when you're distracted. It's calculated psychological warfare.

![](https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1766841795340/315f3516-40a1-4987-857c-fc77b5520df4.avif align="center")

---

And because you repeat the same tasks, even normal sounds become terrifying. That embalming pump? After a few hours, it feels like a jump scare every time.

## **The Night Before Launch: Pure Panic**

After two years working alone—modelling, coding, designing, everything himself—Clarke hit launch day.

The night before, he had a **breakdown**. Convinced the game wasn't scary. Convinced people would hate it. Every solo developer's nightmare.

Then it launched.

![](https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1766841831327/14083443-51e0-4bd5-b1b9-188a8f6bae7c.png align="center")

---

Became a Steam bestseller. Streamers went crazy for it. Made nearly **ONE MILLION** **DOLLARS** in the first month.

Clarke didn't just save his indie career—he crushed it.

## **What We Can Learn**

The Mortuary Assistant teaches us: sometimes weird ideas are the ones that work.

Clarke tested his concept with a one-week prototype before investing years. He let players tell him what they wanted. He turned into advantages. Rough graphics? That makes it **creepier**.

![](https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1766841856594/16326c11-93a2-4245-b157-5f0707373580.png align="center")

---

He also made the horror personal. The demon doesn't just randomly scare you—it uses Rebecca's trauma, her mother's death, her **guilt**. That connection makes every scare hit harder.

Most importantly? He broke his massive goal ("finish game") into tiny tasks ("model four trees today"). That's how you survive **solo development** without losing your mind.

**The Afterlife**

Today, The Mortuary Assistant has a Definitive Edition with new content and is getting a **FILM ADAPTATION**. Clarke went from bedroom developer to Hollywood.

He's now working on a Paranormal Activity game, proving that taking the "dumb" risk was the smartest move of his career.

![](data:image/png;base64, align="center")

---

So next time you're thinking about chasing a weird dream, remember: a guy quit Disney to make a game about embalming haunted corpses, and it made him a millionaire.

Maybe doing something a little dumb is exactly what you need.
